WEBVTT

00:01.135 --> 00:03.336
They've offered me a position.

00:03.470 --> 00:05.404
<i> [thunder echoes]</i>

00:05.406 --> 00:07.006
<i> - Elspeth Hunter,</i>

00:07.141 --> 00:09.542
<i> confined to Blackwell's Island</i>
<i> Asylum for two years</i>

00:09.677 --> 00:13.078
<i> for attempted murder</i>
<i> of her own mother.</i>

00:13.214 --> 00:14.413
- She went to school
with children

00:14.549 --> 00:17.082
from the finest families
in Brooklyn.

00:17.084 --> 00:18.684
- Aspirations.

00:18.819 --> 00:20.485
- So you fabricated a story
about her trying to kill you?

00:20.621 --> 00:22.487
<i> You created a killer.</i>

00:22.489 --> 00:24.823
- The madwoman had a child
of her own.

00:24.825 --> 00:27.560
<i> - He's gone behind my back</i>
<i> and used that child</i>

00:27.695 --> 00:29.695
<i> to lure Libby out of hiding.</i>

00:29.830 --> 00:30.863
- [chokes]

00:32.299 --> 00:35.434
<i> - What have you done with her?</i>

00:35.436 --> 00:39.372
<i> - I want not to be alone,</i>
<i> childless, lonely.</i>

00:39.506 --> 00:41.774
<i> - If you love him,</i>
<i> you must tell him, Sara.</i>

00:41.909 --> 00:45.178
<i> A time will come</i>
<i> when it's too late.</i>

00:45.312 --> 00:50.750
- Put the gun down or he dies.

00:52.987 --> 00:57.656
[heavy breathing]

00:57.658 --> 01:01.394
- Stay away from me,
or I'll kill him.

01:01.528 --> 01:04.329
- You don't want
to do that, Libby.

01:04.331 --> 01:05.598
You know that you don't.

01:05.733 --> 01:08.267
- No, you--

01:08.403 --> 01:10.469
you don't know anything.

01:10.471 --> 01:12.605
- Put the knife down.

01:12.740 --> 01:16.609
- Tell me where she is.

01:16.744 --> 01:18.477
- Put the knife down
and I'll tell you.

01:18.613 --> 01:20.679
- You're lying!
- No.

01:20.681 --> 01:23.816
- Those are lies!
- No, no.

01:23.951 --> 01:26.151
<i> [ominous music]</i>

01:26.287 --> 01:30.223
Please, let him live.

01:30.357 --> 01:33.158
- Why?

01:33.294 --> 01:35.228
Because he's your beau?

01:35.362 --> 01:40.699
Oh, oh, because you love him?

01:40.835 --> 01:44.236
[chuckles softly]
All right.

01:44.371 --> 01:47.440
I'll count to two.

01:47.575 --> 01:50.443
One.
- [groans]

01:50.578 --> 01:53.779
- She's
at the Kreizler Institute!

01:56.917 --> 01:58.317
- What?

01:58.453 --> 02:00.252
You--you put--you put her

02:00.387 --> 02:01.520
in a--

02:01.522 --> 02:07.860
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:07.995 --> 02:09.662
[growls]

02:09.797 --> 02:11.330
- Where is the baby?

02:11.332 --> 02:14.267
- That baby?

02:14.401 --> 02:15.534
He ain't mine.

02:15.536 --> 02:16.869
- What have you done with him?

02:17.004 --> 02:22.407
- [laughs]

02:22.543 --> 02:25.410
<i> [dark music]</i>

02:25.546 --> 02:32.451
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:55.176 --> 02:58.043
[indistinct chatter]

02:58.179 --> 03:01.280
[dogs barking]

03:11.058 --> 03:12.657
- Carotid artery.

03:12.659 --> 03:15.594
It would've been quick,
if that's any consolation.

03:15.596 --> 03:20.199
- Man walks a beat
half his life for what?

03:20.335 --> 03:21.734
For this?

03:21.869 --> 03:23.669
- He died in his uniform
serving the city.

03:23.804 --> 03:25.338
- Serving
the propertied poltroons

03:25.472 --> 03:27.472
with greenbacks
in their pockets.

03:27.474 --> 03:29.542
It's what we do, Marcus.

03:29.677 --> 03:30.943
You think there'd an army
of men out there

03:31.078 --> 03:33.078
hunting for your baby?

03:33.080 --> 03:34.514
Or his?

03:37.352 --> 03:39.018
[flash powder bangs
and sizzles]

03:39.020 --> 03:41.620
Does he need to suffer
this further indignity?

03:41.622 --> 03:43.222
We know who done the deed.

03:43.224 --> 03:46.025
- Photographs will help
the prosecution, Mr. Burns.

03:55.703 --> 03:58.303
- Who would've thought
a newspaper man's occupation

03:58.305 --> 04:00.406
would be this hazardous?

04:03.378 --> 04:05.411
[clears throat]

04:14.722 --> 04:17.190
What's the plan?

04:17.324 --> 04:21.326
- We need to interview Libby.

04:21.462 --> 04:25.264
John--

04:25.400 --> 04:27.533
I thought I'd lost you.

04:31.739 --> 04:35.207
What are we going to do?

04:35.342 --> 04:36.809
- We'll find a way.

04:36.944 --> 04:39.344
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

04:39.480 --> 04:42.147
Is that not what you want?

04:42.149 --> 04:46.151
- I just fear that you love
this Sara Howard,

04:46.287 --> 04:49.021
your friend,

04:49.156 --> 04:51.624
and all the qualities that
you like in me as a friend,

04:51.759 --> 04:54.493
you would not want in a wife.

04:54.495 --> 04:57.096
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:57.098 --> 05:02.101
- I love you for your kindness
and your courage,

05:02.103 --> 05:06.972
your beauty,
and your fierce intelligence.

05:07.108 --> 05:08.974
You challenge me.

05:09.110 --> 05:12.044
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:12.179 --> 05:14.046
What are you scared of, Sara?

05:14.181 --> 05:16.115
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:16.250 --> 05:20.453
- Love that is not truthful
is not love.

05:20.588 --> 05:24.657
It's only passion.

05:24.792 --> 05:28.327
Is it not true that you want
a wife, a family,

05:28.329 --> 05:30.529
a place to call home?

05:30.531 --> 05:32.665
That's what you want?

05:32.800 --> 05:37.270
- Is that so wrong?
- No.

05:37.404 --> 05:41.274
But at this moment,
I'm not sure that I--

05:41.408 --> 05:48.181
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:49.350 --> 05:52.285
You need rest.

05:52.419 --> 05:55.288
- That child is alive,
I know it.

05:55.422 --> 05:58.491
I'm coming with you.
[groans]

05:58.625 --> 06:00.826
- We must hurry.

06:00.961 --> 06:03.228
Laszlo is meeting us
at the station.

06:03.364 --> 06:07.166
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:07.168 --> 06:08.433
<i> [keys jingle]</i>

06:08.569 --> 06:15.675
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:24.319 --> 06:25.384
[bucket clanks]

06:25.386 --> 06:28.387
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

06:28.389 --> 06:33.258
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:33.260 --> 06:35.861
- I talked to Mulberry Street,
Mr. Byrnes,

06:35.997 --> 06:38.130
and they're happy for you
to conduct the interview,

06:38.265 --> 06:41.600
given your knowledge
of the situation.

06:41.602 --> 06:48.774
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:07.161 --> 07:08.361
- Ordinarily,

07:08.495 --> 07:11.096
I'd talk to someone
such as yourself first.

07:11.098 --> 07:13.699
That would be the first degree.

07:13.834 --> 07:17.703
And if the truth
weren't forthcoming,

07:17.838 --> 07:20.906
I'd subject you
to the second degree.

07:21.042 --> 07:23.376
I broke all creation
and all nature

07:23.510 --> 07:25.644
and all wrath in my time.

07:25.646 --> 07:27.180
Even the toughest ones crack

07:27.314 --> 07:32.117
when they've been subjected
to the Byrnes' third degree.

07:32.119 --> 07:34.253
Gentlemen.

07:34.389 --> 07:41.527
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:45.866 --> 07:48.968
[chaotic splashing]

08:00.615 --> 08:02.881
- I will return tomorrow
to check on her.

08:02.883 --> 08:04.349
- I appreciate it.

08:04.485 --> 08:06.218
And while these matters are
brought to their conclusion,

08:06.353 --> 08:09.154
you and I have another
pressing issue to discuss.

08:09.156 --> 08:13.358
- We might not have the time.

08:13.360 --> 08:14.693
- Vienna.

08:14.695 --> 08:18.764
- A decision must be made
imminently.

08:18.899 --> 08:20.766
- I hadn't imagined
you would go.

08:20.768 --> 08:23.436
- And I hadn't imagined
you would stay.

08:23.570 --> 08:25.971
- [chuckles]

08:26.107 --> 08:29.275
- I can't decline an invitation
from Dr. Freud.

08:33.848 --> 08:38.117
- As much as I'm tempted
to go with you,

08:38.119 --> 08:40.653
my life is here.

08:40.788 --> 08:43.122
- All windows and doors here
are secure.

08:43.124 --> 08:45.390
- Would you and Lucius remain
here while I'm gone?

08:45.392 --> 08:46.659
- Of course.

08:50.665 --> 08:53.332
- [sighs]

08:53.468 --> 08:56.269
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

08:56.403 --> 09:03.376
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:04.946 --> 09:08.147
[indistinct chatter]

09:21.228 --> 09:22.628
- Goo Goo.

09:24.765 --> 09:27.099
Goo Goo.

09:27.234 --> 09:29.902
<i> [soft suspenseful music]</i>

09:31.839 --> 09:35.641
Hold off.
It's me.

09:35.776 --> 09:39.512
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:39.647 --> 09:43.115
[dog barking]

09:43.250 --> 09:45.650
- [fusses]

09:45.652 --> 09:47.720
- The cops got Libby.

09:47.855 --> 09:50.589
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:50.725 --> 09:51.924
- How?

09:52.059 --> 09:54.393
- One of our guys
saw her dragged in.

09:54.529 --> 09:58.731
- [fusses]
- So what you gonna do with it?

09:58.866 --> 10:00.866
- I don't know.

10:00.868 --> 10:03.936
Not sure
if Libby wants it no more.

10:04.071 --> 10:08.107
Maybe leave it.
- [fusses]

10:09.476 --> 10:12.845
- [gasping and coughing]

10:15.883 --> 10:19.952
- Are you gonna talk?
- [pants]

10:20.087 --> 10:21.754
- Again.

10:21.889 --> 10:24.957
[water sloshing
and bucket clattering]

10:29.030 --> 10:32.831
- [gasping and coughing]

10:32.967 --> 10:34.967
- Where is the child?

10:35.102 --> 10:37.904
- [rasps indistinctly]

10:39.707 --> 10:42.708
Wait, wait, wait,
wait, wait, wait, wait, wait.

10:42.710 --> 10:44.109
- Hang on.

10:44.111 --> 10:45.378
- [rasping] I'll tell you
where the baby is.

10:45.512 --> 10:46.912
[rasping] I'll tell you
where the baby is.

10:46.914 --> 10:48.847
- What?
What did she say?

10:48.849 --> 10:50.249
- I'll tell you...

10:50.385 --> 10:51.516
where...

10:51.518 --> 10:54.653
- [screams]
Get her off me, get her off!

10:54.655 --> 10:55.921
[moans]

10:56.057 --> 10:58.457
- Get him out of here!

10:58.593 --> 10:59.858
- [spits]

10:59.994 --> 11:04.863
[chuckling]

11:04.999 --> 11:07.867
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

11:08.002 --> 11:09.602
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:09.737 --> 11:10.936
[laughs]

11:10.938 --> 11:14.874
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:15.009 --> 11:17.276
- Mr. Byrnes, I must protest.

11:17.278 --> 11:19.344
I do not approve of
merciless methods of torture,

11:19.480 --> 11:21.213
no matter what someone
has done.

11:21.348 --> 11:23.816
- It's easy to cast aspersions
from where you stand,

11:23.951 --> 11:26.619
Miss Howard.
You have that luxury.

11:26.754 --> 11:28.754
I, on the other hand, don't,

11:28.889 --> 11:30.823
no matter
how difficult the task.

11:30.958 --> 11:33.225
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:33.360 --> 11:35.360
- It is not a bad thing
to feel guilt.

11:35.496 --> 11:37.362
It furnishes the mind
with the possibility of change.

11:37.498 --> 11:40.032
- Oh, don't start talking
about me, now.

11:40.167 --> 11:43.102
You and your postulations.

11:43.104 --> 11:50.276
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:57.585 --> 11:59.051
I can't break her.

11:59.186 --> 12:02.455
- You can't break someone who's
already broken, Mr. Byrnes.

12:04.525 --> 12:06.459
- Why don't you have a go
at her, see ifs...

12:06.594 --> 12:09.362
one of your claptrap theories
can't open her up?

12:14.401 --> 12:17.170
- It's worth a shot.
What have you to lose?

12:22.677 --> 12:24.143
- It's one night, Lucius.

12:24.279 --> 12:27.980
Just until Laszlo finds
a suitable place for her.

12:29.284 --> 12:31.016
- Do I look like
I'm complaining?

12:31.018 --> 12:33.219
- Yes, yes, you do.

12:40.561 --> 12:41.694
Are you comfortable?

12:41.829 --> 12:43.095
- Quite.

12:43.230 --> 12:44.497
- [chuckles]

12:45.833 --> 12:47.232
Did I tell you
about the dream

12:47.234 --> 12:49.969
I had the other night
about Mama?

12:49.971 --> 12:52.371
She asked me
to meet her midday

12:52.507 --> 12:56.709
on Hester Street under
the clock outside Mendel's.

12:56.844 --> 13:00.445
- Mendel's?

13:00.581 --> 13:02.381
What happened?

13:02.517 --> 13:06.452
- I waited under the clock.
She didn't show up.

13:09.123 --> 13:10.890
What do you think that means?

13:14.061 --> 13:15.928
- That you miss her.

13:21.936 --> 13:23.536
<i> [keys jingle]</i>

13:23.671 --> 13:26.739
- Not yet.

13:26.874 --> 13:28.807
- What is it?

13:28.943 --> 13:30.209
- You do not know
how to approach her?

13:30.345 --> 13:31.744
- On the contrary, I do,

13:31.879 --> 13:36.349
but we don't have time
for her to know me and I her.

13:36.483 --> 13:41.086
It would serve us better if--
- If I were to interview her.

13:41.222 --> 13:43.822
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

13:43.958 --> 13:46.291
She needs a doctor.

13:46.293 --> 13:48.961
I fear I'm not qualified.
- You're immensely qualified.

13:49.096 --> 13:51.030
- She's entirely deranged.

13:51.165 --> 13:54.299
Surely it's not safe for Sara
to be in there alone with her.

13:54.301 --> 13:56.169
- They have treated this
poor creature with violence.

13:56.303 --> 13:59.504
She will distrust
any unfamiliar face.

13:59.506 --> 14:00.973
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:01.108 --> 14:02.641
You and Libby share a bond.

14:02.777 --> 14:04.910
You know her.
You met her.

14:04.912 --> 14:06.178
You studied her.

14:06.313 --> 14:09.582
You know who she is.

14:09.717 --> 14:13.518
- You're right.
I'll do it.

14:13.654 --> 14:16.121
<i> [ominous music]</i>

14:16.123 --> 14:20.259
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:20.395 --> 14:23.528
- If you need us,
we'll be here.

14:23.664 --> 14:30.102
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:34.341 --> 14:37.542
- Hello, Libby.

14:37.544 --> 14:40.413
- You're not frightened of me?

14:40.547 --> 14:45.751
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:45.886 --> 14:47.686
You should be.

14:47.688 --> 14:50.022
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:55.062 --> 14:57.930
[indistinct chatter]

14:58.065 --> 15:01.133
[water dripping]

15:06.674 --> 15:10.075
- They hurt you?

15:10.077 --> 15:14.079
- Men have always hurt me.

15:14.081 --> 15:18.684
- I know about your mother.
- Mm. [sighs]

15:18.819 --> 15:23.022
She lied, you know?
My mother.

15:23.024 --> 15:25.691
First time I went
to Blackwell Island

15:25.693 --> 15:27.826
when my father died,

15:27.962 --> 15:32.265
when I came out with a child,
she cut herself.

15:34.369 --> 15:35.935
She said I did it.

15:37.504 --> 15:39.838
She didn't want a baby.

15:39.840 --> 15:43.042
She didn't want me.

15:43.044 --> 15:46.111
She didn't want me to have it,
so they--

15:46.113 --> 15:50.349
they look the baby
from me because of her.

15:52.587 --> 15:58.523
- I'm of the opinion that some
people shouldn't have children.

15:58.525 --> 16:02.194
They do it because
they think they're supposed to,

16:02.329 --> 16:05.731
but it's not really
what they want.

16:05.866 --> 16:09.868
Is that the way
your mother was?

16:09.870 --> 16:12.204
- Yeah.

16:12.339 --> 16:13.806
- Mine, too.

16:16.477 --> 16:18.411
- She didn't love you?

16:23.550 --> 16:26.952
Your father, he--

16:26.954 --> 16:30.022
he loved you, though,
didn't he?

16:32.093 --> 16:36.895
- I always felt, as a child...

16:36.897 --> 16:38.497
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

16:38.633 --> 16:42.301
That if he did love me,

16:42.437 --> 16:44.369
why did he leave me?

16:44.505 --> 16:48.307
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

16:48.443 --> 16:53.979
But I was happy
before Pop died.

16:54.115 --> 16:55.914
- Me, too.
[chuckles]

16:55.916 --> 17:00.453
I was always happy.
[chuckles]

17:00.588 --> 17:04.723
I had these pretty dresses,
taffeta and silk,

17:04.859 --> 17:09.128
and I--I did ballet dancing.

17:09.130 --> 17:11.730
I knew all the moves:

17:11.732 --> 17:14.733
pirouettes and arabesques.

17:14.869 --> 17:17.336
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:17.472 --> 17:21.874
- But having Clara--

17:22.009 --> 17:25.811
that made you happy...

17:25.946 --> 17:30.683
to feel loved, didn't it?

17:30.818 --> 17:35.620
- When she was born,

17:35.622 --> 17:37.556
she was covered in blood,

17:37.558 --> 17:42.361
and they wiped her down,
and they laid her on me,

17:42.363 --> 17:46.098
and from that moment,
I loved her.

17:46.233 --> 17:51.904
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:52.039 --> 17:55.374
- Would you like to see her?

17:55.510 --> 17:57.576
Clara?

17:57.578 --> 18:02.848
Because I could bring her
to you if you like.

18:02.984 --> 18:05.851
- You--you'd bring her to me?

18:05.853 --> 18:09.254
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

18:09.256 --> 18:12.525
- But you would have to tell me
where the baby is.

18:12.660 --> 18:19.632
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

18:35.350 --> 18:38.551
- Sara?

18:38.686 --> 18:42.021
When can I see her?
Clara?

18:47.028 --> 18:48.427
- Lock the door.

18:48.563 --> 18:49.762
- Wait.

18:49.897 --> 18:52.497
<i> [dark music]</i>

18:52.499 --> 18:53.432
Wait!

18:53.568 --> 18:56.035
- She told me
where the baby is.

18:56.037 --> 18:58.637
- No, no, no!

18:58.639 --> 19:02.241
No, no!

19:02.377 --> 19:04.509
Sara!

19:04.645 --> 19:07.512
- Mr. Byrnes,
we have an address.

19:07.648 --> 19:08.513
- Murphy.
- Sir?

19:08.649 --> 19:09.915
- Round up your boys.
We're leaving.

19:09.917 --> 19:10.916
- Yes, sir.

19:10.918 --> 19:14.119
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

19:14.121 --> 19:15.320
[cocks gun]

19:15.322 --> 19:16.589
- Come on, come on, come on.

19:16.724 --> 19:18.323
- Keep it moving, lads.
Come on, hurry up.

19:18.459 --> 19:20.525
Those damn Dusters
will be waiting, no doubt.

19:20.527 --> 19:23.196
- On the double!
[indistinct chatter]

19:23.330 --> 19:24.863
- Ready?

19:24.999 --> 19:26.866
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

19:27.001 --> 19:28.067
- [muttering angrily]
You bitch.

19:28.202 --> 19:30.535
You bitch.

19:30.671 --> 19:34.207
- I fear I have been
unnecessarily cruel to her,

19:34.341 --> 19:36.208
and yet, I had to deceive her.

19:36.343 --> 19:38.277
- As she deceived you?

19:38.413 --> 19:40.879
- I lied.
I said I would bring her Clara.

19:40.881 --> 19:42.748
- You found out
where the child is.

19:42.750 --> 19:45.350
That is what matters.

19:45.352 --> 19:47.086
[horse neighs]
- Hyah!

19:47.088 --> 19:51.824
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

19:51.959 --> 19:53.092
- Watch yourselves!

19:53.227 --> 20:00.132
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

20:04.639 --> 20:06.171
- Boys, lads.

20:06.307 --> 20:10.776
There's a light on in there.
You two, cover the back.

20:10.778 --> 20:13.312
- Ready yourselves, boys.

20:13.448 --> 20:16.515
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

20:16.651 --> 20:21.920
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

20:21.922 --> 20:23.922
- Sir, over here.

20:23.924 --> 20:25.458
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

20:25.593 --> 20:26.459
[hammer clicks]

20:26.594 --> 20:29.328
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

20:29.464 --> 20:30.863
- Come out, or we shoot!

20:30.998 --> 20:32.865
[wings flutter]

20:33.000 --> 20:35.400
[pigeons cooing]

20:35.536 --> 20:37.936
They've taken flight, it seems.

20:37.938 --> 20:41.474
- [fusses]

20:41.609 --> 20:44.743
- [barks]

20:44.745 --> 20:47.212
- No, don't shoot the damn dog,
man.

20:47.348 --> 20:49.148
It's just an animal.

20:49.284 --> 20:51.417
- [fusses]

20:54.489 --> 20:57.490
[crying]

20:57.625 --> 20:59.492
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

20:59.626 --> 21:01.360
- It's all right, little man.

21:01.362 --> 21:05.630
- [crying]
- It's all right. [shushes]

21:05.632 --> 21:07.766
It's all right, little man.

21:07.902 --> 21:10.035
- Is he all right?

21:10.171 --> 21:13.839
- Yes.

21:13.841 --> 21:16.909
We should take him
to a hospital.

21:17.044 --> 21:20.313
It's all right.
[shushes]

21:20.447 --> 21:22.181
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

21:22.317 --> 21:24.717
[train rattling]

21:24.852 --> 21:27.720
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

21:27.855 --> 21:29.989
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

21:30.124 --> 21:33.192
- Sir, what now?

21:33.194 --> 21:34.727
- Escort the baby
to the hospital,

21:34.862 --> 21:36.529
and we'll notify Vanderbilt.

21:36.663 --> 21:37.796
- Sir.

21:37.798 --> 21:44.770
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

21:55.216 --> 21:57.016
- What's the plan?

21:57.018 --> 21:59.084
- We're gonna make
these sorry sons of bitches

21:59.086 --> 22:01.621
wish they'd never been born.

22:05.826 --> 22:08.995
[indistinct chatter]

22:13.534 --> 22:15.267
- Is there nothing else
we can do for her?

22:15.403 --> 22:17.536
- Her mind is in great turmoil.

22:17.672 --> 22:18.937
- [humming to self]

22:19.073 --> 22:22.008
- At the very least, we should
insist she see a doctor.

22:22.142 --> 22:24.577
She needs medical treatment.

22:31.151 --> 22:34.687
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

22:34.822 --> 22:37.289
[indistinct shouting]

22:37.291 --> 22:38.757
[chain rattles]

22:38.759 --> 22:45.264
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

22:47.101 --> 22:49.836
[gunshot]
- This way!

22:49.970 --> 22:53.239
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

22:53.374 --> 22:55.574
[heavy thudding]

22:55.710 --> 22:57.376
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

22:57.378 --> 22:59.712
- You'll be safe in there.
[lock clicks]

22:59.714 --> 23:01.848
[indistinct shouting]

23:01.982 --> 23:03.181
Take the keys.

23:03.317 --> 23:09.187
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

23:09.323 --> 23:10.923
[shouting]

23:10.925 --> 23:12.124
- Goo Goo.
- Libby?

23:12.260 --> 23:13.860
- Goo Goo!
- Libby!

23:13.994 --> 23:16.662
- I'm here, Goo Goo!
- Libby!

23:16.797 --> 23:18.865
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

23:18.999 --> 23:21.133
- Open the door.
Open the door.

23:21.135 --> 23:22.601
[lock clicking]

23:22.737 --> 23:24.403
Where's that bitch?

23:24.538 --> 23:27.940
I know she's here.
I know she's here.

23:27.942 --> 23:28.941
I can smell her.

23:29.077 --> 23:31.610
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

23:31.746 --> 23:36.682
- Libby, we gotta go.
The cops are gonna come back.

23:36.817 --> 23:38.951
- I need Clara.

23:38.953 --> 23:40.286
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

23:40.421 --> 23:44.222
I need Clara.
- Let's go.

23:44.358 --> 23:51.464
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

24:47.021 --> 24:48.821
[glass shatters]

24:50.959 --> 24:54.026
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

24:54.162 --> 24:56.362
- Hey, hey, wake up.

24:56.497 --> 24:59.097
Wake up.
Someone's here.

24:59.099 --> 25:05.705
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

25:09.243 --> 25:10.308
- [cocks gun]

25:10.310 --> 25:13.512
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

25:13.648 --> 25:15.314
- Marcus.

25:15.449 --> 25:17.249
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

25:17.251 --> 25:19.785
- Where's my daughter?

25:19.920 --> 25:21.119
- You can't take her.

25:21.255 --> 25:24.390
- [scoffs]
I can't take my own daughter?

25:35.670 --> 25:38.537
- [clicks hammer]
Hey, what are you doing?

25:38.673 --> 25:41.841
[gun blasts]
- [grunts]

25:55.289 --> 25:58.156
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

25:58.292 --> 26:05.398
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

26:14.775 --> 26:17.043
- Hi.

26:17.177 --> 26:19.245
Hey.
[gasps]

26:19.380 --> 26:21.914
Clara, come here.

26:21.916 --> 26:24.383
Hey.

26:24.385 --> 26:26.985
It's me.
[chuckles]

26:27.121 --> 26:30.122
I'm your mama.

26:30.258 --> 26:31.924
And you're gonna come with me.

26:32.060 --> 26:33.392
- Come on, let's go.

26:33.394 --> 26:35.394
- [stutters]
Oh, this?

26:35.529 --> 26:37.195
This isn't anything.

26:37.331 --> 26:39.265
- [gasps]
- Now come on.

26:39.400 --> 26:42.635
Good girl, good girl.

26:43.738 --> 26:44.537
- [grunts]

26:44.672 --> 26:47.005
- Oh, it's okay.
I'm your mama.

26:47.141 --> 26:48.006
- Ow!

26:48.142 --> 26:49.141
- Don't hurt her!

26:49.143 --> 26:51.143
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

26:51.145 --> 26:52.411
[door latch clicks]

26:52.546 --> 26:53.846
[door slams]

27:12.967 --> 27:14.800
- My glasses broke.

27:21.041 --> 27:23.976
Marcus?

27:23.978 --> 27:24.977
Marcus.

27:26.180 --> 27:27.980
Marcus!

27:27.982 --> 27:30.116
- [mumbles]

27:30.250 --> 27:31.850
- Uh, stop the bleeding.

27:31.986 --> 27:33.986
- Stay with me.

27:33.988 --> 27:36.989
- What?
I have to stop the bleeding.

27:38.793 --> 27:41.393
You're all right.
- [mumbles]

27:41.529 --> 27:43.462
- Marcus?
- [exhales and grunts]

27:43.597 --> 27:45.731
- You're all right.

27:45.866 --> 27:47.466
- [chuckles]

27:47.468 --> 27:50.603
[breathes raggedly]

27:52.406 --> 27:54.873
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

27:54.875 --> 27:56.875
- Marcus.

27:56.877 --> 28:00.078
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

28:00.214 --> 28:01.880
Don't leave me.

28:02.016 --> 28:04.750
- It's okay.

28:04.885 --> 28:11.858
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

28:12.560 --> 28:16.963
- Marcus, Marcus.

28:17.097 --> 28:24.070
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

28:25.506 --> 28:28.507
Please don't leave me, Marcus.

28:28.643 --> 28:33.245
[sobbing]

28:33.247 --> 28:39.051
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

28:39.053 --> 28:44.023
[praying in Hebrew]

28:53.935 --> 28:58.871
- [prays in Hebrew]

29:00.542 --> 29:02.474
My the Lord comfort you

29:02.610 --> 29:05.378
with all the mourners
of Zion and Jerusalem.

29:08.549 --> 29:11.417
- Lucius, you have
my deepest condolences.

29:11.552 --> 29:15.020
Marcus was one of our own,
as are you.

29:15.022 --> 29:16.756
The both of yous.

29:20.027 --> 29:21.394
- Go right ahead.

29:31.172 --> 29:33.705
- He was taken
from you far too soon.

29:33.707 --> 29:35.174
I'm so sorry.

29:36.844 --> 29:38.377
- Lucius.

29:41.115 --> 29:43.515
- I know.

29:43.651 --> 29:45.318
John.

29:47.989 --> 29:49.555
- I'm so very sorry.

29:56.998 --> 30:00.800
- I couldn't pull the trigger.

30:00.934 --> 30:02.134
I'm useless.

30:02.136 --> 30:04.203
- Don't say that.

30:04.338 --> 30:06.472
He loved you,
and you loved him.

30:06.608 --> 30:09.675
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

30:09.811 --> 30:16.749
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:26.227 --> 30:28.694
- It feels so fleeting,
this life.

30:28.830 --> 30:31.697
Gust of wind, and the flame
is extinguished.

30:31.699 --> 30:35.967
- Man makes plans,
and the gods laugh.

30:35.969 --> 30:37.436
- In the hospital,
you asked me,

30:37.571 --> 30:38.970
did I want a family?

30:38.972 --> 30:41.641
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:41.775 --> 30:44.310
- And you said that you did.

30:44.445 --> 30:47.313
- I have dreamt about it often,

30:47.448 --> 30:49.715
but I realize here in this room

30:49.717 --> 30:54.053
what it is I value most dearly
in life.

30:54.188 --> 30:57.389
I was born a gentleman.

30:57.391 --> 30:58.524
I have grown accustomed
to behaving

30:58.526 --> 31:00.526
in a certain, correct way,

31:00.662 --> 31:06.198
not quite saying what it is
I want and what I don't want.

31:06.334 --> 31:08.000
- What do you want?

31:08.002 --> 31:11.203
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

31:11.205 --> 31:13.138
- I want you.

31:13.140 --> 31:18.878
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

31:20.948 --> 31:22.715
- [sighs]

31:24.618 --> 31:26.752
- What's on your mind?

31:29.023 --> 31:33.025
- Dr. Stratton has been offered
a posting in Vienna.

31:33.027 --> 31:37.296
- Are you thinking
of accompanying her?

31:37.431 --> 31:39.498
Whatever it is you decide,

31:39.633 --> 31:42.902
you must place
your own happiness first.

31:43.037 --> 31:45.505
- What of you, Sara?

31:48.242 --> 31:50.309
- John means the world to me.

31:53.781 --> 31:57.316
And yet, I fear
we desire different things.

31:57.451 --> 31:59.518
- But there's more?

31:59.653 --> 32:02.854
- I feel pulled
every which way.

32:02.990 --> 32:05.257
- You should abide
by your own advice.

32:05.393 --> 32:06.658
[door latch clicks]

32:06.660 --> 32:13.799
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:14.936 --> 32:16.202
- This is from Lucius.

32:16.337 --> 32:17.537
Everything the police collected

32:17.671 --> 32:20.406
over the course
of the investigation.

32:20.541 --> 32:21.941
- Let us begin, then.

32:22.076 --> 32:28.814
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:28.816 --> 32:31.883
Laszlo, you said that Libby
was a frightened child herself.

32:32.019 --> 32:33.819
- Her emotional growth
was likely stunted

32:33.821 --> 32:35.621
by the repeated trauma
she had suffered.

32:35.757 --> 32:37.556
- There was a moment
in the prison cell,

32:37.691 --> 32:40.626
in the midst of recounting
the horrors that befell her,

32:40.628 --> 32:44.229
her eyes lit up
at a recollection

32:44.231 --> 32:45.631
where she spoke of being happy,

32:45.767 --> 32:49.034
of doing ballet,
of pretty dresses.

32:49.170 --> 32:50.502
- She aspired to be a lady.

32:50.504 --> 32:51.971
- If her mother
was being truthful,

32:52.106 --> 32:53.639
they were more
than aspirations.

32:53.641 --> 32:57.042
It was a life they once had--
a paradise lost.

32:57.178 --> 32:59.445
- Lost when her father died.

32:59.580 --> 33:01.046
- She's sheltering here
in her memories.

33:01.182 --> 33:02.582
They do not disappoint her.

33:02.716 --> 33:04.716
The more of a whirlwind
she reaps in the present,

33:04.852 --> 33:06.718
the more her mind seeks refuge
in the past.

33:06.854 --> 33:08.854
- She's retreating
to a time when she was happy,

33:08.856 --> 33:10.790
the halcyon days of childhood.

33:10.924 --> 33:14.393
- Perhaps this is the house
in which she lived.

33:14.528 --> 33:15.661
It was in a painting
on the wall

33:15.797 --> 33:18.597
at Malorie Hunter's apartment.

33:18.732 --> 33:20.399
- If this was
her childhood home--

33:20.534 --> 33:22.602
- Now reunited
with her daughter,

33:22.736 --> 33:24.470
her own family unit
is complete.

33:24.606 --> 33:26.606
All that's left is...
- To go home.

33:26.740 --> 33:28.740
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

33:28.742 --> 33:30.275
- Bitsy,
call Sergeant Kelly in Brooklyn

33:30.277 --> 33:33.012
and get the address
of the old Hunter family home.

33:33.147 --> 33:34.279
We need to alert Byrnes.

33:34.281 --> 33:35.881
I believe he does want
to help us.

33:35.883 --> 33:39.284
This time,
we leave nothing to chance.

33:39.286 --> 33:42.087
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

33:42.223 --> 33:45.090
- [humming softly]

33:45.226 --> 33:52.164
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

34:08.650 --> 34:09.649
And again.

34:09.783 --> 34:11.517
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

34:11.519 --> 34:13.519
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

34:13.521 --> 34:15.587
[hooves clopping]

34:15.589 --> 34:19.525
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

34:19.661 --> 34:21.593
- Whoa, whoa!

34:21.729 --> 34:26.265
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

34:26.400 --> 34:27.399
- Rope that off!

34:27.535 --> 34:28.800
- She's in there.

34:28.802 --> 34:30.802
We've identified Libby Hatch
inside

34:30.804 --> 34:33.472
with Goo Goo Knox
and the child.

34:33.607 --> 34:35.140
We believe if we go in
all guns blazing,

34:35.276 --> 34:38.610
the child is lost,
and this could be a trap,

34:38.612 --> 34:40.079
so my boys must stand prepared

34:40.214 --> 34:42.882
for another attack
by those Dusters.

34:43.017 --> 34:45.885
Miss Howard, I'll set up
a perimeter watch.

34:46.020 --> 34:49.221
You let me know
what assistance I can offer.

34:49.357 --> 34:50.356
- Thank you, Mr. Byrnes.

34:50.491 --> 34:54.059
[indistinct chatter]

34:54.762 --> 34:56.362
- We'll begin
with the demi-plié.

34:56.364 --> 34:58.698
You bend your knees, keep your
heels firmly on the ground.

34:58.832 --> 35:00.832
- Libby,
the kid don't wanna dance.

35:00.968 --> 35:02.568
What is this place, anyway?

35:02.570 --> 35:04.503
- I already told you,
you idiot.

35:04.638 --> 35:06.772
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

35:06.908 --> 35:10.442
I used to live here.

35:10.578 --> 35:13.178
- [chuckles]

35:13.180 --> 35:17.249
I don't think so.
This place is a goddamn palace.

35:17.385 --> 35:24.490
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

35:32.466 --> 35:34.666
- You heard that?

35:34.802 --> 35:41.908
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

35:42.744 --> 35:44.343
[glass shatters]
Shh!

35:44.478 --> 35:51.350
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

35:51.485 --> 35:54.353
[floorboards creaking]

35:54.488 --> 35:59.224
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

35:59.226 --> 36:03.095
Clara, come--come here.

36:03.230 --> 36:04.964
Clara.

36:05.099 --> 36:07.967
Clara.

36:08.102 --> 36:10.302
Clara.

36:10.304 --> 36:14.173
Clara, I'm--I'm your mom.

36:14.308 --> 36:16.776
I'm your mom, Clara.

36:16.910 --> 36:20.446
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

36:20.581 --> 36:24.917
Why--why--why are you so mean?

36:25.052 --> 36:26.986
No, no, no, no, no, no.

36:27.121 --> 36:29.789
- Ow, ow!

36:29.923 --> 36:31.523
- [shushes]

36:31.659 --> 36:33.859
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

36:33.995 --> 36:37.062
- I thought we had rats.
[cocks gun]

36:37.064 --> 36:39.065
- [gasps]

36:40.802 --> 36:44.937
- [muffled shouts]
- [shushing]

36:58.019 --> 37:01.287
- Help me--ow!
- Clara.

37:01.422 --> 37:03.422
You need to call Byrnes.

37:03.557 --> 37:05.691
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

37:05.827 --> 37:07.026
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

37:07.161 --> 37:08.760
- Come here.
- [whimpers]

37:08.896 --> 37:10.362
- Good girl, good girl.

37:10.364 --> 37:12.764
- Ow, ow!
- Shut up.

37:12.766 --> 37:15.767
I'm your mom.

37:15.769 --> 37:18.170
Why don't you want--
- Libby.

37:18.172 --> 37:20.439
- No, no.

37:20.574 --> 37:21.907
- Let her go.

37:22.043 --> 37:26.646
- No, she's mine,
and you're not gonna take her.

37:26.780 --> 37:28.848
[glass breaks]
- Libby, don't.

37:28.983 --> 37:32.784
- I'll take her with me,
where no one is gonna hurt her.

37:32.920 --> 37:37.189
- You're hurting her.

37:37.191 --> 37:41.193
- No, but--

37:41.329 --> 37:43.663
but I love her.

37:43.797 --> 37:45.997
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

37:45.999 --> 37:48.734
I loved her
the moment she was born.

37:48.870 --> 37:52.271
I loved her since
she was a baby in my arms.

37:52.406 --> 37:54.406
- What happened to you
does not determine

37:54.408 --> 37:57.609
what Clara will become.

37:57.745 --> 38:00.212
She has her life ahead of her.

38:00.348 --> 38:01.681
- Look at her.

38:01.815 --> 38:05.417
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:05.419 --> 38:07.819
- [sobs and sniffles]

38:07.955 --> 38:14.626
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:14.628 --> 38:17.629
<i> [infant squalling]</i>

38:17.631 --> 38:23.402
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:24.772 --> 38:25.905
[glass shatters]

38:26.040 --> 38:32.444
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:32.446 --> 38:35.314
- The only thing

38:35.449 --> 38:41.520
that ever loves you
is that little, innocent thing,

38:41.655 --> 38:46.858
and you think maybe...

38:46.994 --> 38:50.529
maybe it will stop the pain.

38:50.664 --> 38:52.998
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:53.000 --> 38:58.337
And it does, for a--
for--for a little while.

38:58.472 --> 38:59.805
- Do not shoot!

38:59.941 --> 39:03.809
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

39:03.811 --> 39:05.811
- I'm sorry.

39:05.813 --> 39:10.750
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

39:10.884 --> 39:13.953
I'm sorry, I'm sorry,

39:14.088 --> 39:19.024
I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

39:19.026 --> 39:22.027
[sniffles and sobs]

39:22.029 --> 39:29.202
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

39:33.841 --> 39:35.440
- "New York Times!"
Duster slain!

39:35.442 --> 39:37.977
- "New York Journal!"
Knox gone!

39:38.112 --> 39:41.714
[indistinct chatter
and phones ringing]

39:41.849 --> 39:44.383
- Oh, no, thank you.

39:44.385 --> 39:46.451
- Well, congratulations, John.

39:46.587 --> 39:47.720
I heard on the down low

39:47.855 --> 39:49.254
Vanderbilt
is singing your praises.

39:49.256 --> 39:51.190
- I thought
he was keeping it hush-hush.

39:51.326 --> 39:53.526
- I got my own sources, too.

39:53.661 --> 39:56.329
We thought when you hit a high,
you'd leave us.

39:56.463 --> 39:57.796
- And forego my scoop

39:57.798 --> 39:59.798
on the Lying-In Hospital
and Dr. Markoe?

39:59.934 --> 40:01.400
Never.
- [chuckles]

40:01.402 --> 40:04.469
- You know, Bernie,
I've spent most of my life

40:04.605 --> 40:07.673
being somewhat
of a phony, a fake,

40:07.675 --> 40:11.877
but for whatever reason,
I feel I belong here.

40:12.013 --> 40:13.946
- [chuckles]
What about Hearst?

40:14.081 --> 40:15.548
You tell him
about the promotion yet?

40:15.683 --> 40:19.485
- Well, that's complicated.
- [chuckles]

40:20.555 --> 40:22.455
- Would you excuse me
for a moment, Bernie?

40:28.896 --> 40:30.429
I've been informed that

40:30.431 --> 40:33.766
this promotion allows me
to pick my team.

40:33.901 --> 40:37.102
I would very much like it
if you were on it, Joanna.

40:37.104 --> 40:40.305
Stay here.
Work for me, with me.

40:40.441 --> 40:42.975
- Thank you, John...

40:43.110 --> 40:47.112
but I found a newspaper
in Weeksville, in Brooklyn.

40:47.114 --> 40:50.515
It's somewhat more--
- Radical?

40:50.517 --> 40:52.018
- Progressive.

40:53.520 --> 40:56.822
- You've got a visitor,
Mr. Moore.

41:01.996 --> 41:03.229
- Violet.

41:09.003 --> 41:11.003
- Papa said
you've made quite the splash

41:11.138 --> 41:13.606
with your stories
about Libby Hatch.

41:13.741 --> 41:17.676
- Yes, well, it's been quite
a taxing experience.

41:17.812 --> 41:19.745
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

41:19.747 --> 41:21.680
- You've been a stranger to me
of late.

41:21.682 --> 41:24.549
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

41:24.685 --> 41:29.622
- Violet, I wanted to, um--

41:29.757 --> 41:32.357
I need to explain something
to you.

41:32.359 --> 41:35.160
- I feel we do need to talk.

41:35.296 --> 41:42.201
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

41:44.305 --> 41:48.307
- Laszlo Kreizler,
meet Frederick Douglass.

41:48.309 --> 41:51.043
I've been meaning to give it
to you for quite some time.

41:51.178 --> 41:53.178
The occasion just
never felt fitting.

41:53.314 --> 41:55.448
- I'm deeply touched,
my friend.

41:55.582 --> 41:57.382
I will treasure it.

41:57.518 --> 41:59.452
- Let me fill you up.

41:59.586 --> 42:02.121
What's on your mind, Laszlo?

42:02.123 --> 42:05.258
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

42:05.392 --> 42:06.992
- The Institute.

42:06.994 --> 42:10.195
I feel at times that I've been
hiding behind its walls,

42:10.197 --> 42:14.399
and yet, it's my life's work,
and it has given me great joy.

42:14.401 --> 42:15.734
- You know, Laszlo,

42:15.736 --> 42:17.470
the whole time
I was at the Institute,

42:17.604 --> 42:20.606
I never felt like
I was being me.

42:20.741 --> 42:23.142
- And you do here?
- Oh, yeah.

42:23.278 --> 42:24.810
This is my own place,

42:24.812 --> 42:29.414
and I can decide what it is
I want to do for myself.

42:29.550 --> 42:31.150
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

42:31.152 --> 42:32.685
- Despite all my knowledge
of life

42:32.820 --> 42:35.488
and my own advice to patients,

42:35.623 --> 42:37.956
I hesitate.

42:37.958 --> 42:42.094
I tread gingerly when
I should step purposefully.

42:42.229 --> 42:45.564
- If there is no struggle,
there is no progress.

42:45.566 --> 42:48.167
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

42:48.303 --> 42:49.635
Sometimes, Laszlo,

42:49.770 --> 42:52.771
you just have
to decide what it is you want

42:52.773 --> 42:55.574
and then fight for it.

42:55.576 --> 42:59.712
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

43:09.190 --> 43:11.390
- What on Earth are you doing,
Miss Howard?

43:11.526 --> 43:12.925
- [chuckles]

43:13.060 --> 43:16.261
I'm trying to take the bullets
out of my furniture.

43:16.263 --> 43:18.664
- That's quite the weapon
you have there.

43:18.799 --> 43:21.400
- Oh, there.

43:21.536 --> 43:23.202
[bullet clinks]
[sighs]

43:23.338 --> 43:25.338
What, this?

43:25.472 --> 43:27.673
This is a Balkan dagger.

43:27.808 --> 43:31.677
It's proven to be quite useful.

43:34.349 --> 43:36.115
What is it?

43:38.019 --> 43:40.353
John, nothing is so bad
that you cannot tell me.

43:40.487 --> 43:42.822
Grasp the nettle,
and it hardly stings.

43:46.961 --> 43:49.762
- Violet is
in a delicate condition.

43:56.503 --> 43:59.504
- Dare I ask?

43:59.506 --> 44:01.307
- I'm the father.

44:07.715 --> 44:09.815
- I am happy for you, John.

44:11.652 --> 44:14.787
I am sad, but I am also happy.

44:17.392 --> 44:20.993
Because now,
you get what your heart desires

44:21.128 --> 44:24.263
and that is to be a father.

44:24.265 --> 44:27.666
You said that it didn't matter,
but...

44:27.668 --> 44:29.402
I suspect that it did.

44:29.536 --> 44:31.871
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

44:32.006 --> 44:34.206
- I'm so sorry, Sara.

44:34.341 --> 44:36.675
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

44:36.811 --> 44:39.879
- Desiring a child of your own
is nothing to be ashamed of.

44:40.014 --> 44:42.881
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

44:42.883 --> 44:47.019
It's a new life,
a new Schuyler Moore.

44:47.154 --> 44:48.754
- [chuckles]

44:48.889 --> 44:50.956
[inhales deeply]

44:51.092 --> 44:54.627
And all this time,

44:54.762 --> 44:57.696
there's been an ache
in my heart,

44:57.698 --> 45:02.435
an emptiness
ever since my brother died,

45:02.569 --> 45:06.505
and it may sound foolish,

45:06.507 --> 45:08.241
but I hope, perhaps,

45:08.375 --> 45:12.377
that if a small part of him
were to be born again,

45:12.379 --> 45:15.514
that I would see it
in my own child,

45:15.650 --> 45:18.250
or my own child in him.

45:18.385 --> 45:20.786
- That doesn't sound foolish.

45:20.921 --> 45:24.857
- Doesn't?
- No.

45:24.992 --> 45:28.661
Sounds beautiful.

45:28.796 --> 45:29.862
[chuckles]

45:29.997 --> 45:37.069
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

45:42.009 --> 45:44.810
- You play chess
so romantically, Laszlo,

45:44.945 --> 45:46.545
with such daring,

45:46.681 --> 45:48.347
gallantly accepting my gambits,

45:48.349 --> 45:51.416
and yet, still
mercilessly ruining me.

45:51.552 --> 45:52.951
- [chuckles]

45:52.953 --> 45:54.687
- Perhaps you play
with such reckless abandon

45:54.822 --> 45:57.422
because there's little
at stake.

45:57.424 --> 45:59.158
There's no risk.

45:59.160 --> 46:02.227
Knight to king's knight seven,
knight takes pawn.

46:02.229 --> 46:03.628
Check.

46:03.630 --> 46:06.431
- King to queen one.

46:06.567 --> 46:08.100
Are you offering a wager?

46:08.235 --> 46:11.636
- Queen
to bishop's knight six.

46:11.638 --> 46:13.306
Check.

46:13.440 --> 46:14.773
Indeed.

46:14.775 --> 46:19.312
Should you lose, then you're
mine to do with as I so wish.

46:22.449 --> 46:25.985
- I fear at this moment, I
would have an unfair advantage.

46:26.120 --> 46:28.587
What you suggest sounds
positively Faustian.

46:28.723 --> 46:31.056
You mean
to take my immortal soul.

46:31.058 --> 46:34.927
Yet hardly likely, Karen,

46:35.062 --> 46:38.864
when my knight takes
your queen.

46:39.000 --> 46:41.667
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

46:41.669 --> 46:46.605
- Perhaps merely
your mortal body, then?

46:46.741 --> 46:49.542
Checkmate.

46:49.677 --> 46:54.347
I do believe I did say to do
with you as I so pleased.

46:54.481 --> 46:56.882
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

46:57.018 --> 47:01.086
Are you sure I can't tempt you
to come to Europe with me?

47:01.088 --> 47:03.889
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

47:03.891 --> 47:06.892
[children shouting and playing]

47:06.894 --> 47:11.898
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

47:14.369 --> 47:16.301
- I'm sure the Institute
would thrive

47:16.303 --> 47:18.437
or even prosper without me.

47:18.439 --> 47:21.707
I've realized
I'm not some omniscient god.

47:21.709 --> 47:22.841
- That's quite
the breakthrough, Laszlo,

47:22.977 --> 47:24.243
to know one is not divine.

47:24.379 --> 47:28.513
- [chuckles]
Yes, I'm simply a man,

47:28.649 --> 47:32.585
quite an imperfect creature.

47:32.720 --> 47:33.786
But your arrival in my life

47:33.921 --> 47:36.655
has precipitated a desire
to change.

47:36.657 --> 47:37.623
I most--

47:42.597 --> 47:45.664
- Don't change too much.

47:45.666 --> 47:48.467
I like the man you are.

47:52.673 --> 47:55.608
- Tell me--

47:55.743 --> 47:59.011
how is the weather in Vienna
this time of the year?

47:59.146 --> 48:05.684
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

48:05.686 --> 48:07.753
- We shall miss you, Laszlo.

48:07.755 --> 48:10.489
- And I, you, both of you,

48:10.491 --> 48:13.226
but this is the time
for melancholia.

48:13.360 --> 48:16.629
- And so, we find ourselves
here once again.

48:16.764 --> 48:18.964
- "One of the most beautiful
qualities of friendship

48:19.100 --> 48:22.301
is to understand
and to be understood."

48:22.303 --> 48:25.104
- Seneca the Younger, I think.

48:25.106 --> 48:26.371
I did attend some
of the classes

48:26.373 --> 48:28.173
in our Harvard days, Laszlo.

48:28.175 --> 48:29.908
- [chuckles]

48:29.910 --> 48:32.177
- To our friendship.

48:32.179 --> 48:35.180
[classical music playing]

48:35.182 --> 48:38.383
♪ ♪

48:38.385 --> 48:39.718
- I hope there will still
be occasion

48:39.720 --> 48:42.387
for us to dine together
when I return.

48:42.523 --> 48:44.523
- If you return.

48:44.659 --> 48:46.125
- [chuckles]

48:46.127 --> 48:50.195
♪ ♪

48:50.197 --> 48:53.132
- Well, my carriage awaits.

48:53.134 --> 48:56.469
♪ ♪

48:56.604 --> 48:58.871
Laszlo, be well.

48:59.006 --> 49:02.007
♪ ♪

49:02.143 --> 49:05.010
Goodbye, Miss Sara Howard.

49:05.146 --> 49:06.879
- Goodbye, John Moore.

49:07.014 --> 49:09.882
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

49:10.017 --> 49:17.190
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

49:17.892 --> 49:21.027
[indistinct chatter]

49:28.369 --> 49:30.970
So how long will you be
in Europe for?

49:30.972 --> 49:32.838
- I'm not sure.

49:32.840 --> 49:34.840
Six months, perhaps longer.

49:34.976 --> 49:35.975
- And you'll have
Professor Stratton

49:35.977 --> 49:37.843
to share the adventure with.

49:37.979 --> 49:41.581
Shall we drink to that?

49:44.051 --> 49:47.252
- American bourbon,
straight up.

49:47.254 --> 49:50.523
And for Miss Howard?

49:50.657 --> 49:52.291
- Make it two.

49:56.331 --> 50:03.469
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

50:37.304 --> 50:42.041
[takes deep breath]

50:44.178 --> 50:45.378
- My father, he--

50:45.512 --> 50:48.181
<i> he had an accident, too.</i>

50:48.315 --> 50:55.488
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

50:58.125 --> 51:01.526
<i> I thought we understood</i>
<i> each other, Miss Howard,</i>

51:01.662 --> 51:05.731
<i> but you--you're incapable.</i>

51:05.866 --> 51:12.772
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

51:21.682 --> 51:25.350
<i> And you think</i>
<i> maybe it will stop the pain.</i>

51:25.486 --> 51:32.592
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

51:37.832 --> 51:40.099
- Morning.
We have a busy day.

51:40.234 --> 51:41.366
Bitsy?

51:41.502 --> 51:43.168
- I sent Ida down
to the Tenderloin

51:43.170 --> 51:45.370
to get the lowdown
on the Annie Swede case,

51:45.506 --> 51:47.840
and the commissioner
is asking you to assist

51:47.975 --> 51:49.508
on
the Pacific State Bank heist.

51:49.510 --> 51:51.310
- Good.
Set up a meeting.

51:51.312 --> 51:52.978
We need access
to all the evidence.

51:53.114 --> 51:54.780
- Mrs. Schermerhorn messaged.

51:54.915 --> 51:57.582
- Servants are stealing
her silverware again?

51:57.584 --> 51:59.785
Politely decline, I think.

51:59.787 --> 52:01.386
Girls, I would like
to introduce

52:01.388 --> 52:05.458
the newest member
of our team, Kitty Byrnes.

52:05.592 --> 52:08.461
- I appreciate the opportunity,
Miss Sara.

52:08.595 --> 52:09.929
I won't let you down.

52:10.064 --> 52:12.397
- You will not see a lot
of photographs of detectives

52:12.533 --> 52:14.867
that look like us
in the "Police Gazette," Kitty,

52:15.002 --> 52:16.201
not yet, anyways.

52:16.203 --> 52:18.403
But I think of it like this:

52:18.539 --> 52:21.874
our office at 808 Broadway
is lit by electricity,

52:22.009 --> 52:25.610
and before electricity,
people used kerosene lamps,

52:25.612 --> 52:29.615
and before that, they used
candles made from whale oil,

52:29.750 --> 52:32.818
and the man
with the whale oil candle

52:32.820 --> 52:36.021
could never have envisioned
all of this.

52:36.023 --> 52:37.823
We may be judged as women,

52:37.825 --> 52:41.226
but we must remember
that we are detectives,

52:41.362 --> 52:43.162
and whether we wear skirts
or trousers

52:43.298 --> 52:45.230
is immaterial to what we do.

52:45.232 --> 52:47.232
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

52:47.234 --> 52:50.369
It's human nature
to make mistakes, Kitty.

52:50.505 --> 52:52.705
We sometimes might fail,

52:52.840 --> 52:57.442
but we should not be defined
by our failures.

52:57.578 --> 53:01.580
It's 8:00.
Let us begin.

53:01.716 --> 53:04.783
[phones ringing]
[indistinct chatter]

53:04.919 --> 53:09.388
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

53:09.390 --> 53:10.990
Bitsy.

53:10.992 --> 53:17.997
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

53:17.999 --> 53:21.000
[indistinct chatter]

53:21.002 --> 53:24.003
[hooves clopping]

53:24.005 --> 53:26.138
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

53:26.273 --> 53:29.141
[newsboy crying]

53:29.276 --> 53:36.449
<i> ♪ ♪</i>
